For implementing two stacks by using a single array we can simply take int variables say top1 = -1 and top2 = n, top1 represent the current position of the element in stack1 and top2 represent the current position of the element in stack2. 
Listed below is the code of push, pop, and top for both stacks.

**Stack1 :**

    /*** push **/
    void push_stack1(int element_value ){
        if (top1 &gt;= top2 -1 )
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;array if full (overflow)&quot;;
        else
            arr[++top1] = element_value;
    }

    /*** pop ***/
    int pop_stack1 (){
        if(top1 &lt; 0)
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;no element in stack1 under-flow&quot;;
        else
            cout &lt;&lt; arr[top1--];
    }

    /*** top ***/
    int top_stack1(){ 
        if (top1 &lt; 0)
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;stack1 is smepty &quot;;
        else 
            cout &lt;&lt; arr[top1];
    }

**Stack2 :** 

    /*** push **/
    void push_stack2(int element_value ){
        if (top2 &lt;= top1 + 1 )
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;array if full (overflow)&quot;;
        else
            arr[--top2] = element_value;
    }


    /*** pop ***/
    int pop_stack2 (){
        if(top2 &gt; n-1)
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;no element in stack2 under-flow&quot;;
        else
            cout &lt;&lt; arr[top2++];
    }

    /*** top ***/
    int top_stack2() { 
        if (top2 &gt; n-1)
            cout &lt;&lt; &quot;stack2 is smepty &quot;;
        else 
            cout &lt;&lt; arr[top2];
    }

On every full check, you can implement the following:

    bool ifFull(int top1,int top2){
        if(top2-top1==1)
           return true;
    return false;
    }
But if the program is a part of larger program, then there can be a more optimised way using bitwise-XOR.

    bool ifFull(int top1,int top2){
        if((top2-top1)~1)
           return false;
    return true;
    }

In contrast to previous method which uses a logical and an arithmetic operator, the second method only uses an arithmetic and a bitwise operator which is comparatively faster.

